  "prompt": "What is the stage 2 hypertension diet?",
  "response": "Stage 2 hypertension is characterized by significantly elevated blood pressure levels, typically a systolic pressure of 140 mmHg or higher or a diastolic pressure of 90 mmHg or higher. Managing this condition often requires a combination of lifestyle changes, including dietary modifications, along with medication as prescribed by a healthcare provider. Here\u2019s an overview of a diet that can help manage stage 2 hypertension:\n\n---\n\n### **Key Principles of a Stage 2 Hypertension Diet**\n1. **Reduce Sodium Intake**  \n   - Aim for less than 1,500\u20132,300 mg of sodium per day.  \n   - Avoid processed foods, canned soups, fast food, and salty snacks.  \n   - Use herbs, spices, and salt-free seasoning blends instead of salt.\n\n2. **Increase Potassium-Rich Foods**  \n   - Potassium helps counteract the effects of sodium.  \n   - Include foods like bananas, oranges, spinach, sweet potatoes, avocados, and beans.\n\n3. **Follow the DASH Diet (Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension)**  \n   - Emphasize fruits, vegetables, whole grains, lean proteins, and low-fat dairy.  \n   - Limit saturated fats, cholesterol, and added sugars.\n\n4. **Choose Whole, Unprocessed Foods**  \n   - Focus on whole grains, fresh produce, lean meats, fish, and legumes.  \n   - Avoid processed and packaged foods high in sodium and unhealthy fats.\n\n5. **Limit Alcohol**  \n   - Men should limit to 2 drinks per day, and women to 1 drink per day (if consumed).\n\n6. **Reduce Saturated and Trans Fats**  \n   - Avoid fried foods, fatty cuts of meat, and baked goods with trans fats.  \n   - Opt for healthier fats like olive oil, nuts, seeds, and fatty fish (e.g., salmon).\n\n7. **Increase Magnesium and Calcium Intake**  \n   - Include foods like leafy greens, nuts, seeds, dairy, and fortified plant-based milk.\n\n8. **Stay Hydrated**  \n   - Drink plenty of water and limit sugary beverages.\n\n---\n\n### **Sample Daily Meal Plan**\n- **Breakfast:** Oatmeal topped with fresh berries and a sprinkle of flaxseeds, served with a glass of low-fat milk.  \n- **Snack:** A small handful of unsalted almonds and an orange.  \n- **Lunch:** Grilled chicken salad with mixed greens, cucumbers, tomatoes, olive oil, and vinegar dressing, plus a whole-grain roll.  \n- **Snack:** Carrot sticks with hummus.  \n- **Dinner:** Baked salmon with quinoa and steamed broccoli.  \n- **Dessert (optional):** A small piece of dark chocolate (70% cocoa or higher).\n\n---\n\n### **Additional Tips**\n- Monitor portion sizes to maintain a healthy weight.  \n- Increase physical activity (e.g., 30 minutes of moderate exercise most days).  \n- Avoid smoking and manage stress through relaxation techniques like yoga or meditation.  \n- Regularly monitor blood pressure and follow up with your healthcare provider.\n\nAlways consult a healthcare professional or registered dietitian to create a personalized plan tailored to your specific needs and health conditions.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
